| Notes                   = * {{WP|Shailene Woodley}} was initially cast as [[Mary Jane Watson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2012/10/19/confirmed-shailene-woodley-for-mj-in-spider-man-2-and-3?abthid=5081b1974feb735f550003df|title=Confirmed: Shailene Woodley for MJ in Spider-Man 2 and 3|work=IGN|last=Nicholson|first=Max|date=October 19, 2012|accessdate=October 19, 2012}}</ref> In June 2013, Woodley revealed that her scenes had been cut from the film, and instead was planned appear in the third film in the franchise, which never happened.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.superherohype.com/news/articles/177605-mary-jane-wont-appear-in-the-amazing-spider-man-2-role-pushed-to-third-film|title=Mary Jane Won't Appear in The Amazing Spider-Man 2, Role Pushed to Third Film|last=Perry|first=Spencer|date=19 June 2013|accessdate=19 June 2013|work=SuperHeroHype!}}</ref> Canadian actress Sarah Gadon, whose casting was announced later the same day, was rumored to replace Woodley in the role for the next film, but Gadon confirmed this was not the case via her Twitter account.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/SarahGadon/status/348219630403321857|title=To all those a twitter, I will not be playing MJ in Spider-Man. I have a role in the film, but it is not that one :)|last=Gadon|first=Sarah|date=21 June 2013|accessdate=21 June 2013}}</ref>
* ''The Amazing Spider-Man 2'' is the first Spider-Man film to film entirely in New York.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424127887323826704578356840396252864.html?mod=googlenews_wsj|title=Tax-Policy Web Lures 'Spider-Man' Film Here|last=Kusisto|first=Laura|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=12 March 2013|accessdate=18 March 2013}}</ref> New York governor {{WP|Andrew Cuomo}} has also called the film the "biggest movie production in New York history."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amny.com/urbanite-1.812039/spider-man-s-newest-flick-creates-super-economic-boon-for-state-1.4808929|title=Spider-Man's newest flick creates super economic boom for state|last=Pereira|first=Ivan|work=AM New York|date=13 March 2013|accessdate=18 March 2013}}</ref>
* Shooting for the film wrapped on June 25, 2013, after 100 days of filming.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/MarcW/status/349545683218481152|title=That's a wrap.  Thanks!|last=Webb|first=Marc|date=25 June 2013|accessdate=27 June 2013}}</ref>
* The film received mixed reviews from critics, with a 53% from Rotten Tomatoes. Peter and Gwen's chemistry received positive reviews, alongside Dane DeHaan's performance and visual effects.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_amazing_spider_man_2/|title=Rotten Tomatoes Reviews}}</ref>
[[File:Venom from The Amazing Spider-Man 2 (film) altered scene 001.jpg|thumb|right|Final Cut of the film with [[Rhino Armor]] (top) and the Trailer shot showing a [[Venom (Symbiote)|Venom]] like creature]]
* In shots released in the trailers, a being that resembled the [[Symbiotes|symbiote]] [[Venom (Symbiote)|Venom]] appears in one the display cases that the [[Gustav Fiers (Earth-120703)|The Gentleman]] walks past. In the final cut of the film, this scene was altered and the [[Rhino Armor]] appeared instead.

| Trivia                  = * The film and its release date were announced on August 5, 2011, almost a year prior to the first film's release, and before the first film had finished filming.
* Although the name "The Amazing Spider-Man 2" was colloquially used to describe the film since its announcement, the title of the film was not confirmed until February 05, 2013.<ref name="Official Synopsis"/>
* DCPs for ''The Amazing Spider-Man 2'' were distributed under the alias "Pole." 
* On July 17, 2013, two more installments of the franchise were announced. The third installment was going to be released on June 10, 2016, and the fourth installment on May 4, 2018, making each film two years apart. However, following to the critical and financial underperformance of the film and a hack on Sony Pictures, it was announced that Sony would reboot the series and collaborate with Marvel Studios to bring Spider-Man to the [[Earth-199999|Marvel Cinematic Universe]], cancelling the series.
*This is the third Spider-Man film to be released in May, alongside ''[[Spider-Man (2002 film)|Spider-Man]]'' (2002), and ''[[Spider-Man 3 (film)|Spider-Man 3]]''.
*A mid-credits scene in this film is a promotion for ''[[X-Men: Days of Future Past (film)|X-Men: Days of Future Past]]''. This is due to the fact that Webb had signed on to a film for Fox but left to direct this film, with the scene being a compromise between Fox and Sony.
* Peter Parker mentioning that his pay was fair for 1961 is a reference to the year {{cl|Amazing Adult Fantasy Vol 1}}, the comic series Spider-Man first appeared on, began publishing.<ref>[http://theamazingspidermanblog.com/post/90589111555/in-the-film-peter-parker-remarks-that-his-pay-is The Amazing Spider-Man 2 - Tumblr]</ref>
* The clock in the tower where Gwen Stacy dies stops at 1:21, it was {{cl|Amazing Spider-Man Vol 1 121}} the comic in which Gwen died.

